sentences: Palmer left New Orleans for Hollywood in 1957, initially working for Aladdin Records.
He soon started working with the Wrecking Crew, a loose-knit group of session musicians who recorded nonstop during their heyday from 1962 to 1968.
The musicians union tracked Palmer playing on 450 dates in 1967 alone.
In 1982, Palmer was elected treasurer of the Local 47 of the American Federation of Musicians.
He served until he was defeated in 1984.
He was re-elected in 1990.
A biography, Backbeat: Earl Palmer's Story, by Tony Scherman, was published in 1999.
Palmer died in September 2008, in Banning, California, after a long illness.
He married his fourth wife, Jeline, in 2004.
In 2000, Palmer became one of the first session musicians to be inducted into the Rock and Roll Hall of Fame.
Drumsville (Liberty Records, 1961)
Percolator Twist (Liberty Records, 1962)
Earl Palmer NAMM Oral History Program Interview (2002)
He remained in demand as a drummer throughout the 1970s and 1980s, playing on recordings for albums by Randy Newman, Tom Waits, Bonnie Raitt, Tim Buckley, Little Feat and Elvis Costello.
According to one obituary, "his list of credits read like a Who's Who of American popular music of the last 60 years".
He started drumming with the Dave Bartholomew Band in the late 1940s.

sentences: Earl Cyril Palmer (October 25, 1924 – September 19, 2008) was an American drummer and one of the inventors of Rock and Roll.

Born into a show-business family in New Orleans and raised in the Tremé district, Palmer started his career at five as a tap dancer, joining his mother and aunt on the black vaudeville circuit in its twilight and touring the country extensively with Ida Cox's Darktown Scandals Review.
For more than 30 years he played drums on the soundtracks of many movies and television shows.

Amongst the many artists he worked with were Glenn Yarbrough, Frank Sinatra, Phil Spector, Ricky Nelson, Bobby Vee, Ray Charles, Sam Cooke, Eddie Cochran, Ritchie Valens, Bobby Day, Don and Dewey, Jan and Dean, the Beach Boys, Larry Williams, Gene McDaniels, Bobby Darin, Neil Young, the Pets, The Byrds when they were still known as The Beefeaters, and B. Bumble and the Stingers.
In later years, Palmer played with a jazz trio in Los Angeles.
"You could always tell a New Orleans drummer the minute you heard him play his bass drum because he'd have that parade beat connotation."
